text:
Pine Street, north side, west from William Street (right). The Equitable Building appears at the left top.

July 6, 1915

Wurts Brothers

Pine Street (diagonally across lower portion) at William Street (right margin) as viewed southwestward from No. 1 Cedar Street (at Pearl Street), showing the northern sides (rears) of structures that front on Wall Street. From left to right they are the H.L. Dougherty and Company Building (No. 60-62 Wall Street); the National City Building (No. 52 Wall Street); the Bank of New York Building (No. 48 Wall Street); and the Bank of Manhattan Building. (No. 40 Wall Street). The latter is west of William Street while all the former are east of same. Nestling to the right is the 16 storied structure at the S.E. corner of William and Pine Streets which has been occupied by Kuhn, Loeb and Co. for years, No. 52-54 William Street.

July 7, 1930.

P.L. Sperr

William Street (thru the center), north from Pine Street (foreground, street level not seen) showing roof tops of buildings in the downtown area of Manhattan. The small structure in the center (pitched roof) is the Liverpool, London and Globe Insurance Co. Bldg. It is on the easterly side of this thoroughfare and occupies the frontage from Liberty Street to Maiden Lane. Opposite same is another low building; the Montauk Building which occupies the William Street side and frontage of the block mainly utilized by the Federal Reserve Bank. The photographer in all instances is viewing northward from No. 40 Wall Street.

March 9, 1933.
Views 2&3: March 24, 1933

P.L. Sperr

William Street (right), north from Pine Street (foreground of No. 1, street level not seen), showing mainly the roof top of the irregular quadrangular Federal Reserve Bank that abuts on Liberty and Nassau Streets and Maiden Lane. The low (8 story) Montauk Bldg. occupies the William Street side of this block. On the easterly side and opposite the latter is the Liverpool London & Globe Insurance Co. Bldg. This building has a pitched roof and is clearly discernible in View No. 2. The Royal Insurance Co. Building is to the north of the latter, having a curved corner outline. Shown in the foreground and nearly obscuring the Federal Reserve Bank is the New York Mutual Life Insurance Co. Bldg. The photographer's vantage point is the structure at No. 40 Wall Street and from which he views northward.

Views 1 and 2

P.L. Sperr

58-60 William Street, at the N.E. corner of Pine Street, showing the 7-story Harris Forbes Building (No. 58) and a 4-story structure No. 60 under demolition. Across Pine Street appears the lower stories of the Kuhn, Loeb and Co. Building, No. 54-52, at the S.E. corner.

September 3, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
